The Swimmer environment is a continuous-control task in which a chain of linked segments must move to the right by applying torques at two joints while avoiding unnecessarily large control effort.

The observation is a vector of {{ obs_dim }} values:
- state[0]: angle of the front tip
- state[1]: angle of the first rotor
- state[2]: angle of the second rotor
- state[3]: x-velocity of the tip
- state[4]: y-velocity of the tip
- state[5]: angular velocity of the front tip
- state[6]: angular velocity of the first rotor
- state[7]: angular velocity of the second rotor

The action is a vector of {{ action_dim }} continuous torques in the range [-1, 1].

The policy is a 2-layer neural network:
- layer 1 maps the {{ obs_dim }}-dimensional observation to {{ hidden_dim }} hidden units
- layer 2 maps the {{ hidden_dim }} hidden units to the {{ action_dim }} action values
- the hidden activation is {{ activation }}

You optimize {{ rank }} trainable policy parameters.
Treat them as opaque controls of the neural policy rather than as directly interpretable state-to-action weights.
Each trainable parameter should stay in the range [{{ param_min }}, {{ param_max }}].

Reward favors forward progress while mildly penalizing excessive torque:
- reward = x_velocity - 1e-4 * action^2

Good policies usually discover smooth, coordinated torques that generate stable forward locomotion.
